01:18:43.340 --> 01:18:48.820
dancers use this…they do this…there's an improvisational dance technique called

01:18:48.820 --> 01:18:54.740
flocking, where, you know, if you just follow the person in front of you and I started doing

01:18:54.740 --> 01:18:58.860
this, then we all started doing this and suddenly it looks choreographed, you know?

01:18:58.860 --> 01:19:06.100
So that kind of thing of like the fact that we can just in the spur of the moment do something

01:19:06.100 --> 01:19:07.100
in sync or in unison.

01:19:07.100 --> 01:19:08.100
It's in a residence.

01:19:08.100 --> 01:19:09.100
Yeah, yeah.

01:19:09.100 --> 01:19:16.180
So, you know, so another…what I was going to say is that improvisation is something

01:19:16.180 --> 01:19:22.500
we're born doing in the sense that we're…you know, it's how we explore the world, it's

01:19:22.500 --> 01:19:27.740
how we come to learn about our environments, it's how we learn to do everything, it's

01:19:27.740 --> 01:19:30.860
how we learn to talk, how we learn to eat.

01:19:30.860 --> 01:19:36.220
You know, I mean, very…how we're willing to walk is by a lot of stumbling around and

01:19:36.220 --> 01:19:39.820
eventually finding a path, you know?

01:19:39.820 --> 01:19:44.100
And that's really, to me, we're always doing that.

01:19:44.100 --> 01:19:46.740
So that's a very primal experience.

01:19:46.740 --> 01:19:51.740
And so experiencing that in the course of performance, where, you know, you develop all

01:19:51.740 --> 01:19:56.460
this mastery at these different instruments and stuff, but then you also take yourself

01:19:56.460 --> 01:20:10.780
to this point where this…the sort of ideas side or the kind of intellectual side or

01:20:10.780 --> 01:20:18.740
the deliberate side of you, like the stuff that the part of you that plans what to do

01:20:18.740 --> 01:20:23.980
next and when to do it and how to do it, that seems to become relaxed.

01:20:23.980 --> 01:20:30.020
It's almost like being drunk, actually, when you just make a lot of bad…bad decisions.

01:20:30.020 --> 01:20:37.140
But sort of like having no…well, Charles Lim, you guys may know about his work, he

01:20:37.140 --> 01:20:42.940
did MRIs, FMRI's of people improvising, which is a very strange thing.

01:20:42.940 --> 01:20:48.220
I mean, they were lying down on their backs with a keyboard strapped to them.

01:20:48.220 --> 01:20:52.660
And he had that one control condition where they played a memorized piece, another controlled

01:20:52.660 --> 01:20:58.820
another condition, the test trial where they were asked to improvise on a blues or something

01:20:58.820 --> 01:21:00.940
like that, on a keyboard.

01:21:00.940 --> 01:21:15.220
So then he found that certain cognitive functions are relaxed, like the self-guiding kind of

01:21:15.220 --> 01:21:22.300
the self-consciousness is basically relaxed, and then you find yourself just acting.

01:21:22.300 --> 01:21:27.420
So when there's a sort of unity of thought and action, I guess that's sort of the

01:21:27.420 --> 01:21:31.660
thing that to me is kind of like…I guess it's also been described as a flow state

01:21:31.660 --> 01:21:33.620
and that kind of thing.

01:21:33.620 --> 01:21:43.060
I wonder if that pursuit of that moment and improvisation, that sort of threshold, to

01:21:43.060 --> 01:21:49.300
me I see that as the pursuit of the live experience, like the total live-ness, like being in

01:21:49.300 --> 01:21:53.140
the moment where the future is in the future and the past is in the past and you're sort

01:21:53.140 --> 01:21:56.020
of like right there between them.

01:21:56.020 --> 01:22:03.660
And I 100% agree with you in the improvisational context, but I think that that actually is

01:22:03.660 --> 01:22:08.580
part of all of our experience, even if we're playing a piece of music that we've rehearsed

01:22:08.580 --> 01:22:14.980
a thousand times, like there's still no certainty that the next moment will be what was planned

01:22:14.980 --> 01:22:17.020
or it will be something different.

01:22:17.020 --> 01:22:20.900
And that is a fundamental bit of difference between the live experience and the recorded

01:22:20.900 --> 01:22:23.060
experience.

01:22:23.060 --> 01:22:30.340
And going back to the word body in the title, I think that the sort of live experience is

01:22:30.340 --> 01:22:35.580
the presence of our body in this space, listening to someone play music and not necessarily

01:22:35.580 --> 01:22:41.220
knowing what's next, which is so fundamentally different than listening to a recording.

01:22:41.220 --> 01:22:46.420
And it's true your CD player might die the next moment or things might interrupt the

01:22:46.420 --> 01:22:54.060
listening experience, but the expectation, the sort of like state of listening to a recording

01:22:54.060 --> 01:23:00.100
is one of listening to something that's already been like set in a record, in a recorded

01:23:00.100 --> 01:23:03.820
form, in like a archived form.

01:23:03.820 --> 01:23:06.500
And that doesn't afford this uncertainty.

01:23:06.500 --> 01:23:07.500
Right.

01:23:07.500 --> 01:23:08.980
Still an important pleasure.

